<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Agave</i> <i>deserti</i> is co-dominant in the shrub canopy with <i>Adenophyllum</i> <i>porophylloides</i>, <i>Ambrosia</i> <i>dumosa</i>, <i>Ambrosia</i> <i>salsola</i>, <i>Bebbia</i> <i>juncea</i>, <i>Cylindropuntia</i> <i>acanthocarpa</i>, <i>Cylindropuntia</i> <i>echinocarpa</i>, <i>Ferocactus</i> <i>cylindraceus</i>, <i>Krameria</i> <i>grayi</i>, <i>Larrea</i> <i>tridentata</i>, <i>Pleuraphis</i> <i>rigida</i>, <i>Simmondsia</i> <i>chinensis</i>, <i>Stephanomeria</i> <i>pauciflora</i> and <i>Yucca</i> <i>schidigera</i>. Emergent trees or tall shrubs may be present at low cover, including <i>Fouquieria</i> <i>splendens</i>, <i>Juniperus</i> <i>californica</i> or <i>Pinus</i> <i>monophylla</i>. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text">  Shrubs < 3 m; canopy is open to intermittent. Herbaceous layer is open with annuals seasonally present. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li><i>Agave deserti</i> > 5% absolute cover in the shrub canopy; absolute cover exceeds that of any other woody species (Keeler-Wolf et al. 1998b).</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> Slopes, ridges, hills, hills, arroyos, seasonal watercourse margins. Well-drained soils are rocky or sandy.  </div>
</div>

        
