<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Agave deserti </i>is a perennial that forms basal rosettes of succulent leaves. Most California plants reproduce vegetatively by offsets on fleshy, thick rhizomes, which correspond to the subspecies <i>deserti </i>(Gentry 1982). Individual rosettes flower once, and then die (Turner et al. 1995). Plants produce seed regularly, but unless soil moisture is high, seedling establishment is episodic. Bottomland plants probably disperse vegetatively in floods (Uchytil 1990b). <br/>
<br/>
<i>Agave deserti </i>ranges north and east through the southern and eastern Mojave Desert and south into Mexico. It forms stands only in the western Colorado Desert and adjacent Peninsular Ranges. Stands associate with those of the <i>Eriogonum fasciculatum - Viguiera parishii, Fouquieria splendens, Juniperus californica, Larrea tridentata - Ambrosia dumosa, Larrea tridentata - Encelia farinosa, Cylindropuntia bigelovii, </i>and <i>Yucca schidigera </i>alliances. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
